1. Enable port security on the switchports connected to end hosts.

2. Ping from PC1 to PC2 to generate traffic between them.

3. Use a show command to view the secure MAC addresses on SW1.  PC1's MAC address should be in the table.

4. Check the configuration of SW1's F0/2 interface in the running configuration.  Take note of the configurations.

5. Save the running configuration of SW1, and reload the switch.

6. View the secure MAC addresses on SW1 again.  Is PC1's MAC address still present?

7. Enable sticky secure MAC addresses on the F0/2 interface of SW1, and ping from PC1 to PC2 to generate traffic.

8.  View the secure MAC addresses on SW1, then view the configuration of F0/2 in the running configuration.  What is different?

9. Save the running configuration and reload the switch.

10. View the secure MAC addresses on SW1 again.  Is PC1's MAC address still present?

SW1>en
SW1#conf t
Enter configuration commands, one per line.  End with CNTL/Z.
SW1(config)#int f0/2
SW1(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW1(config-if)#switchport por
SW1(config-if)#switchport port-security 

SW2>en
SW2#conf t
Enter configuration commands, one per line.  End with CNTL/Z.
SW2(config)#int f0/2
SW2(config-if)#switchport mode access
SW2(config-if)#switchport port
SW2(config-if)#switchport port-security 

